<PART LBL="IV"><TITLE><XREFTARGET ID="59292">Models of Parallel Computation</TITLE><PARAGRAPH><BOLD></BOLD><XREF IDREF="93055" TYPE="TITLE">Chapter&nbsp;10, &ldquo;Models of Parallel Computation&rdquo;</XREF><BOLD></BOLD></PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH>Provides an overview of the different models around which you can design a parallel or distributed application in Silicon Graphics systems.</PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH><BOLD></BOLD><XREF IDREF="41755" TYPE="TITLE">Chapter&nbsp;11, &ldquo;Statement-Level Parallelism&rdquo;</XREF><BOLD></BOLD></PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH>Gives an overview of the use of Power Fortran and Power C to execute do-loops across multiple CPUs.</PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH><BOLD></BOLD><XREF IDREF="43999" TYPE="TITLE">Chapter&nbsp;12, &ldquo;Process-Level Parallelism&rdquo;</XREF><BOLD></BOLD></PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH>Describes the use of IRIX processes to execute in parallel within one address space or in multiple address spaces.</PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH><BOLD></BOLD><XREF IDREF="77267" TYPE="TITLE">Chapter&nbsp;13, &ldquo;Thread-Level Parallelism&rdquo;</XREF><BOLD></BOLD></PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH>Describes the use of POSIX threads (IEEE 1003.1c) for parallel execution within a single address space.</PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH><BOLD></BOLD><XREF IDREF="18012" TYPE="TITLE">Chapter&nbsp;14, &ldquo;Message-Passing Parallelism&rdquo;</XREF><BOLD></BOLD></PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH>Describes two different facilities for distributing an application across multiple host computers: PVM and MPI.</PARAGRAPH>
